\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^2-2x+4} & \\ \cline{2-6}
x^3+0x^2+4x-8 & x^3 &+0x^2 &+4x &-8 & \\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^3-2x^2+4x} & & & \\ \cline{2-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-2x^2+8x} & & & \\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-2x^2} &+4x^2 & & & \\ \cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} &+4x^2 &8x & & \\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} &-4x^2 &+8x &-16 & \\ \cline{3-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} &0 &8x &-16 &+0\\
\end{array}
\]Thus, we have $x^3+4x-8=(x-2)(x^2-2x+4)$, so the other two roots are the roots of $x^2-2x+4$. We can find these roots using the quadratic formula: $x=\frac{-(-2)\pm\sqrt{(-2)^2-4(1)(4)}}{2(1)}=1\pm\sqrt{3}i$. 

